article.description:
Margo Dydek scored a season-high 18 points
against her former team as the Connecticut Sun beat the San Antonio
Silver Stars 79-61 on Saturday night.
article.headline: Prodigal Sun: Dydek returns to beat old Stars team
article.linkText: Prodigal Sun: Dydek returns to beat old Stars team
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Margo Dydek scored a season-high 18 points
against her former team and the Connecticut Sun beat the San
Antonio Silver Stars 79-61 on Saturday night.

Besides her 18 points on 9-of-16 shooting, Dydek had eight
rebounds, six blocked shots and four steals. Dydek played in San
Antonio from 2003-04.

The Sun (17-6) have won three straight and six of seven.
Connecticut remained a game ahead of the Detroit Shock for the lead
in the Eastern Conference. The Shock kept pace with Connecticut by
beating the Chicago Sky on Saturday.

San Antonio (11-13) has lost five of six and is losing ground in
the race for the final playoff spot in the West. The Silver Stars
trail fourth-place Seattle by a game and Phoenix by a half-game.
Both of those teams won Saturday.

The Silver Stars had limited options against the 7-foot-2 Dydek,
as 6-6 starting center Chantelle Anderson missed her first game of
the season after sustained a left patella fracture during a loss to
Washington on Friday.

"We really wanted to control under the basket with Chantelle
Anderson missing," said Dydek. "I feel we won because we play well together as a team,
we know the importance of road games and are very comfortable in
first place."

Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored 12 points for the Sun and added
10 rebounds and seven assists. Katie Douglas finished with 15
points while Lindsay Whalen had 13 points and seven assists.

Marie Ferdinand and La Toya Thomas were also missing from the
San Antonio lineup. Ferdinand, who recently gave birth to her first
child, was the team's leading scorer and only All-Star last year.
Thomas is out with a knee injury after averaging almost 10 points
and five rebounds a game.

"Ultimately, it was the lack of depth that cost the Silver
Stars," Connecticut coach Mike Thibault said. "I can only imagine
how hard it is as a coach to look at your bench and see three
starters in street clothes."

The Sun, who are a WNBA-best 8-4 on the road, tied a franchise
record for a regulation game with 25 assists.

Katie Feenstra, a 6-8 second-year player, started in place of
Anderson and had two shots blocked by Dydek in the first 3:12 of
the game. Feenstra ended the game 5-of-15 from the floor for 11
points. She also had 11 rebounds.

Sophia Young led the Silver Stars with 16 points and 11
rebounds.

"Chantelle is a great player for us, and losing her hurt,"
said Young, who had her fourth double-double of her rookie season.
"We'll have to adjust the next couple of games and find ways to
get more offensive."

Connecticut jumped out to a 10-0 lead while the Silver Stars
missed their first six shots. But Erin Phillips, in her second
career start for Connecticut, had three turnovers in a span of 1:10
that helped the Silver Stars cut the lead to 10-6.

San Antonio chipped away and had the Sun's lead down to 22-19 at
the end of the first quarter. The Silver Stars trailed 29-27 with
5:42 remaining in the first half, but the Sun scored the final 11
points of the half to build a 44-29 lead.
